messages.message:
Patch Set 1:

This simplified the AdapterManager code (remove duplication) and allows flexible use/filtering of AdapterFactories from outside if desired.

Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)

This is fine - but I am not sure it is useful.


The new method still does not have a defined return order for two adapter factories handling the same mapping. So it doesn't address the consumers who are relying on behaviour in <= Eclipse 4.21. Going forward I think the same thing happens - consumers use getAdapter, if it does the correct thing they aren't affected until a future refactor. You have just extended it apply to this new factories method too.

If you can come up with a definition that makes it stable and defined the order of factories being returned, then we are moving forward.

BTW this new method won't really solve the recent case in CDT* - If I switched CDT to use factories() and then filtered on them, I would need to filter out the internal factory that returns an org.eclipse.debug.internal.core.commands.TerminateCommand. 

[1] not sure it was intended to though - https://git.eclipse.org/r/c/cdt/org.eclipse.cdt/+/186940

Patch Set 2:

> Patch Set 2:
> 
> (1 comment)
> 
> This is fine - but I am not sure it is useful.
> 
> 
> The new method still does not have a defined return order for two adapter factories handling the same mapping.

There is no way of define any particular order for the exact same mapping without further API enhancements.

> So it doesn't address the consumers who are relying on behaviour in <= Eclipse 4.21.

before Eclipse 4.21 it was not possible to have two adapters for the same mapping 

> Going forward I think the same thing happens - consumers use getAdapter, if it does the correct thing they aren't affected until a future refactor. You have just extended it apply to this new factories method too.

> If you can come up with a definition that makes it stable and defined the order of factories being returned, then we are moving forward.

The order of factories is already well defined by the classorder, the issues first arise the way these factories are actually queried for a value and which value is to be returned.

> BTW this new method won't really solve the recent case in CDT* - If I switched CDT to use factories() and then filtered on them, I would need to filter out the internal factory that returns an org.eclipse.debug.internal.core.commands.TerminateCommand. 

Correct, but if you want to make sure only specific adapterfactories are taken into account you can do:

factories(..., false).filter(f->f.getClass().getName().equals("only.allowed.factory.name")).map(f->f.adapt(...)).findFirst().orElse(null);

Patch Set 2:

Another way would be that we insert a "NullFactory" for not loaded factories, as adapt is allowed to always return null, this would be a valid response and calling with load=false always is dangerous to miss a thing this clearly would be a good way to express this, I'll adjust the PR...

Patch Set 2:

> Correct, but if you want to make sure only specific adapterfactories are taken into account you can do:
> 
> factories(..., false).filter(f->f.getClass().getName().equals("only.allowed.factory.name")).map(f->f.adapt(...)).findFirst().orElse(null);

But I don't want that - I want to exclude the bad factory, as I don't know what the good factories are, I just know one of the bad ones in this case. For GdbLaunch extenders of CDT must provide a subclass of GdbLaunch and then install adapter factories for that subclass to things like ITerminateHandler. If their terminate handler can work without UI (unlikely, but possible) then in GdbLaunch.terminate we'll use that adapter.

Patch Set 5:

I have now added two test-cases that show how the stream could be used on a lower level. If we can agree on this change I'll add a higher-level API to the 'Adapters' class (I think it makes sense to submit this as a separate change).

This will then allow anyone to create what ever behavior they desire later on based on this stream primitive.

Patch Set 5:

Any comments? Build + Test showing use-cases are succeeds so from my side this is fine now.

Patch Set 5:

As usual, it would be useful to have an example of concrete usage of this API in the Eclipse project to ensure there is value to make the maintenance cost worthy. Adding API without clear need for them is just increasing technical debt.

Patch Set 5:

> Patch Set 5:
> 
> As usual, it would be useful to have an example of concrete usage of this API in the Eclipse project to ensure there is value to make the maintenance cost worthy. Adding API without clear need for them is just increasing technical debt.

See the example from Jonah where he likes to check for the *Existence* of a factory without actually loading it.

This is also demonstrated in https://git.eclipse.org/r/c/equinox/rt.equinox.bundles/+/187090/5/bundles/org.eclipse.equinox.common.tests/src/org/eclipse/equinox/common/tests/adaptable/IAdapterManagerTest.java#25
